 and international institutions play in dealing with ethnic conflict. International Law and Ethnic Conflict first covers general philosophical, historical, and cultural issues arising from attempts to apply international law to ethnic conflict. The authors assess the legitimacy of demands based on group identity, the legal rights of ethnic groups, the validity of various entitlement claims, and the meaning of statehood. They then consider the institutional and policy responses of international organizations and states in their attempts to deal with ethnic conflict and analyze the extent to which various forms of intervention prove successful.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aEthnic conflict. 0aInternational law. 4aDiscrimination & Race Relations. 4aPolitical Science & Political History. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Security (National & International).2bisacsh1 aBerman, Nathaniel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrilmayer, Lea, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChayes, Abram, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFarer, Tom, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFisler Damrosch, Lori, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHandler Chayes, Antonia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOrentlicher, Diane F., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPlatzer, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRatner, Steven R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aScheffer, David J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSlaughter, Anne-Marie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTesόn, Fernan